Food for thought from historical case. <p>Xalos <BR>
Outrider of Karana<BR>
Karana</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#CBC6B1><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/bcouncilofguilds.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=kellory>Kellory</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>The Sexless Drood Watchman</span><br> <font color=#8E9173>(10/10/01 1:14:26 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub6.ezboard.com/fcouncilofguildscogplanesraidschedule.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=213.topic&index=7>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Planes leader</span><hr size=1> Yes, what AC did is similar to what Harb and even SD used to do.  However, there are reasons why they dont generally like to do this.  In order for a guild to have a slot on the rotations they must prove they are able to break the plane on their own.  For example Fellowship of Faydark cannot request a slot on the Planes rotation because they are unable to break the plane on their own.<br>
<br>
Now then, if a guild can then presumably they can do much if not all of the plane on their own.  That being the case, opening the raid to CoG would only serve to add in a few extra people to the raid.  Most raids only have between 24-48 people on them.  This is to maximize the amount of loot and keep it to those who need it.  CoG is one of the few groups that will take 55+ people on up.  Different philosophies.  I would also point out that 3-4 groups can effectively clear Fear or even Hate.  Especially if they are 55+.<br>
<br>
What does this mean?  It means if another guild like CoU did it, then they would only be allowing a select few CoG raiders on their raids.  Also, they would be intentionally weakening their own guild since CoG raiders would/should be allowed to roll on all loot.  This means that they are using their time and days to help equip people they will probably never see again.<br>
<br>
In any event, only a very small group of CoG raiders, less than 12 in all likelihood would get to go on any given raid in this fashion.  This is one reason Harb and the Sacred Band eventually stopped running Plane Raids.<br>
<br>
It would really work a whole lot better if a small guild that was not planes capable and not in a planes capable alliance were to look at hosting both the Plane raids and dragon raids.  This would allow for the creation of several raid leaders, hopefully keeping them from burning out.  I'm not stopping a Planes capable guild from doing just what was propsed.  I'm just pointing out why in many cases it doesnt work to well.  If a guild wants to try it, by all means go for it.  But considering how open CoG loot rules are and attendence guidelines are, I dont see it working too well myself.<br>
<br>
But thats just my thoughts.  Perhaps someone has some ideas on how it could reasonably work?  If so, post here.<br>
<br>
Kellory Silverstar<br>
KCoG Plane Raid Liason<br>
